<span class="avatar"></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-2183" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">8</a></span>
<span class="comment_author">Jay Marx</span>
<span class="comment_time">September 10, 2012 at 6:52 pm</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-2183">
<p>If you are unlucky enough to have not yet escaped the Bankrupt Mercenary State (CA), you might confine NM (or other foreign) LLCs to items under $50K (yeah, I know, to BE so lucky!). Untill 2011 there were 5 things that were NOT considered &#8216;doing business in CA&#8221; (to AVOID the now-$800 annual franchise fee( on FOREIGN entities ALSO!)) , and seeking to verify this, I visited <a href="http://www.ftb.ca.gov" rel="nofollow">http://www.ftb.ca.gov</a>, to learn that as of 2011 &#8220;doing business in CA&#8221; is NOW defined as (Revenue &amp;Taxation Code 23101)&#8230;.&#8221;any of the following&#8217;&#8230;.&#8217;(3) The real property and tangible personal property of the taxpayer in this state exceed the lesser of fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) or 25 percent of the taxpayer&#8217;s total real property and tangible personal property.&#8217;&#8230;.. -It used to be HOLDING property was OK &#8211; NO MORE, I guess &#8211; a RE interest or expensive car is now enough to catch their interest.  I was thinking maybe multiple transfers might push it off their radar but no such luck! &#8211; I can&#8217;t wait to escape CA!</p>
</div>
					</dd>
					<dt class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-2184">
<span class="avatar"></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-2184" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">9</a></span>
<span class="comment_author">Jay Marx</span>
<span class="comment_time">September 10, 2012 at 7:03 pm</span>

